{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0ca2c3b0-44e0-11ed-8714-ecf3e43d8190","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"9fa3b094-9feb-4e37-976b-d02e0036ec33","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Working Capital Needs by Industry","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"5b006ee7-3254-49d5-99a4-0c6203d44055"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"2ea6f224-8994-4790-b455-db473f2183b3","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The longer a firm’s cash cycle, the more working capital it has, and the more cash it needs to carry to conduct its daily operations. ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"1552c7eb-cc1c-4f7b-9ed7-262982330189","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Table 19.1","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"91adf2e0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":" provides data on the working capital needs for selected firms in a variety of industries.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"1979d97b-3de8-4752-88eb-3d0f7a5a1658"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":{"$ambrosia":"aero:asset:upload","urn":"urn:aero:cfea5f40-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4","asset":{"urn":"urn:aero:cfea5f40-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"cfea5f40-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4","assetMediaType":"image","assetVisibility":"GLOBAL","ownerId":"e88133a0-8dc4-11eb-964e-4d7e264c9958","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","alfrescoId":"9c3fb003-3ea7-4b91-aaf8-489ce3132df6","name":"TB_19_001.jpg","version":"2.0","lastModifiedDate":1664998753,"lastSyncDate":1665085937},"source":{"small":{"width":691,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cfea5f40-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4/small/f293711a1112151eaa541a408989d6a4.jpeg","height":300},"original":{"width":1381,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cfea5f40-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4/medium/f293711a1112151eaa541a408989d6a4.jpeg","height":600},"medium":{"width":1381,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cfea5f40-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4/medium/f293711a1112151eaa541a408989d6a4.jpeg","height":600},"thumb":{"width":345,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cfea5f40-44e0-11ed-928f-6f45b86fb3a4/thumb/f293711a1112151eaa541a408989d6a4.jpeg","height":150}},"metadata":{"altText":"","workURN":"","caption":"","alfrescoPath":"bronte-e2e-testing-qaint/documentLibrary/BV E2E Test/[10-05-2022] Berk","originalAssetName":"TB_19_001.jpg","longDesc":"","height":"347"}}},"alt":"","caption":"","layout":{"captionPosition":"Below"},"credit":"<p><em>Source</em>: <a class=\"ulink\" href=\"http://www.capitaliq.com\">www.capitaliq.com</a>.</p>","activityLabel":"Table 19.1","activityTitle":"Cash Conversion Cycles of Various Companies (2018)"},"height":347,"ref":"11bdf1b0-16be-4304-b39b-8ab965ff88b6"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"23370902-097f-483b-953e-984045cb97fb","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Because of the characteristics of the different industries, working capital levels vary significantly. For example, a large portion of a retail grocery store’s customers pay cash when they buy their groceries, so you would expect accounts receivable to be a very small percentage of its sales.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"30ae1888-d25e-4386-bbac-7d5b9e2f05d7","stage":{"ref":"3a11383a-74ea-4fdd-910c-d296cc25f4ab","sections":[{"ref":"5b5de25b-4df0-4127-9660-853a49da2884","rows":[{"ref":"ceb08a71-0156-4284-93c5-dcebc5d11e1d","columns":[{"ref":"f3a7783a-4e91-404f-ac1a-7cbc94c3426e","stageElements":[{"ref":"adffbfa1-3123-40e7-8b74-6d4a99dee2e3","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"e05cca81-ea97-42f3-8e7d-59a15fc02a08","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"ec4e7f9b-89ff-44ad-a971-27e270daff4a","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When you use your credit card to pay for your groceries, it is a cash sale for the store. The credit card company pays the store cash upon confirmation of the transaction, even if you do not pay your credit card bill on time.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"1","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"1e119dad-09c3-4f08-b5a2-33f8eedb0d14"},{"object":"text","text":" For Kroger, accounts receivable represent only five days worth of sales. Similar results hold for Southwest Airlines, because many of its customers pay in advance for airline tickets with cash or credit cards. Inventory represents a large percentage of sales for firms such as Lennar, which have a long development and sales cycle. Note also the wide variation in the firms’ cash conversion cycles. For example, Southwest’s cash conversion cycle is negative, reflecting the fact that it receives cash from its customers before having to pay its suppliers.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"66bb967a-922a-4b25-aff4-a43e97466be4"}]}]}]}]},"screenType":"","transitions":{"enter":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""},"exit":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""}},"lockElements":false,"learnerCurrentAttempt":1,"footer":{"buttonText":"Next","buttonIcon":"Arrow","show